        <tr>
          <td colspan="2"><span
class="postbody">Perhaps it is just because I am old-fashioned and such, but I really am quite fond of being able to target certain mobs for their specific loot tables.  
<br />

<br />
I think at any given time there needs to be at least one influential factor to inspire people to raid in general.  Anyone who raids regularly obviously loves to make mobs take dirt naps and the like, but that only goes so far.  Two of the best reasons I can come up with now concerning raids are progression and the obvious loot.  Depending on what game you're playing loot can be a sub-category of progression, just an extra kicker, but so far there isn't much progression action happenin in eq2.  
<br />

<br />
Questing aside, there seems to be no linear progression as to what mobs you should raid in order to become a better player.  Having said this the only other reason to take targets out is to steal their loots.  The idea of randomizing loot tables by putting many items into a pool is definitely a change, but what is the end result?  Given enough time these items will be just as common as if they were dropped from more specific loot tables.  
<br />

<br />
I do like how this randomized loot table makes otherwise useless mobs more useful in that it gives you a reason to go after them.  The problem here being the frustration in attempting to locate a specific item.  Raiding mob after mob for a chance at a good item that has an even yet smaller chance of being the one you may want is more than frustrating.  
<br />

<br />
Where exactly am I leading this conversation?  That I'm not quite sure of just yet, but I do have a take on the matter that I would like to share in order to sum this all up.  I think SOE is replacing content (many mobs with many specific loot tables) with timesinks in the form of chance (fewer mobs with erratic loot tables).  It is true in EQ that mobs, once killed many times over, became useless as far as loot was concerned, but who really wants to play the hamster on the wheel that is feverishly chasing after a *chance*  at good items?
<br />

<br />
In short, take out some of the factors of random! We need some stability, possibly in the form of consitent metal chest drops.</span><span
class="gensmall"></span></td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </td>
