        <tr>
          <td colspan="2"><span
class="postbody">Sidenote: No one heads off Freaks, Gimps and Sickos like Celaen.
<br />

<br />
Main point:
<br />
One possible suggestion I can think of in regards to endgame itemization is to tier the loot tables.  What this proposes is to set different levels of loot tables for the group difficulty of the mob.
<br />

<br />
Groupx2 mobs could carry what the player base sees now in all group situations, minus a chance at metal chests.  Groupx3 could have that same loot table that Groupx2 has but with a definite chance of dropping a Master spell.
<br />

<br />
Groupx4 (a full raid) mobs would have a loot table style similar to Vulak`Aeer from Velious.  Possibility: Twenty-four items broken in to three sets of eight each.  Upon slaying a Groupx4 mob the random number generator selects an item from each set and that would be your reward.
<br />

<br />
What does this lead to?
<br />
1.	Group x2/x3 mobs are left for the people who need t5 rare pieces and other items that would benefit them  as the general assumption behind Groupx4 loot, based upon the small number of x4 mobs, is that one single person will not receive every item they want and thus smaller items (tier 1-3 in Plane of Time being my example) will have to be taken.
<br />
2.	A possible problem that arose during Velious around the Vulak loot table: no one but monks wanted to see Garns Rock, Abashis Staff and Brother Xaves headband in one drop.  In short  class hegemony across the loot table.  While this is not as prevalent in EQ2, thanks to types and not class specific armor, there are key items that say Guardian or Ranger.  Implementation of equal occurrences of loot are not impossible and definitely not a reason to deter from such a suggestion.
<br />

<br />
Comments? Questions?  Gnomes?<br />_________________<br />Azernox
<br />
&lt;Fires of Heaven&gt;
<br />

<br />
Not all is silent in the halls of the dead. Behold the sleeper wakes.</span><span
class="gensmall"></span></td>
